      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In that case, you'll need to rely on more low-level techniques to monitor heap usage and detect memory leaks. One approach is to use a custom memory allocator that provides hooks for you to instrument the code. \n\nFor example, you can modify the standard library's `malloc` and `free` functions to provide a custom memory allocation interface. This will allow you to track the memory allocations and deallocations in your code. \n\nAnother approach is to use a memory tracking library like `jemalloc` or `tcmalloc`, which provide low-level hooks for memory allocation and deallocation. You can use these libraries to instrument your code and track memory usage.\n\nIn terms of manual hooks, you can use assembly language to insert custom code at specific points in your program. For example, you can use a function like `__builtin_return` to insert a custom function call before the return statement. \n\nHere's an example of how you might use assembly language to instrument the `malloc` function:\n```assembly\nvoid* __malloc(size_t size) {\n    // Original malloc implementation...\n    void* ptr = malloc(size);\n    // Insert custom code here...\n    __asm__ __volatile__(\"movl %0, %rax\" : \"=r",
